{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"06130766baa6881e420d7d37e0a44192","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Go is not installed. I can't compile the Go code, but I can still review the code for correctness by reading it carefully.\n\nLet me now systematically identify all the issues and start fixing them. Based on my reading, here are the issues I've found:\n\n### Critical Issues (will break functionality):\n\n1. **webrtc/webrtc.go - WriteVideoFrame is a no-op**: The `WriteVideoFrame` function at line 114-124 does nothing - it just returns nil without actually writing the H.264 frame to the track. This means WebRTC streaming will never work.\n\n2. **api/server.go - handleWebRTCSignal is a no-op**: The function at line 275-283 just calls `c.Next()` which does nothing. There's no actual WebSocket upgrade and no WebRTC signaling handling. The frontend tries to connect to `/api/ws/signal` but this does nothing.\n\n3. **LiveView.vue - WebSocket message format mismatch**: Frontend sends `JSON.stringify({ type: 'offer', payload: pc.localDescription.sdp })` where `payload` is a string (the SDP). But the backend webrtc.go expects `msg.Payload` to be `json.RawMessage` and tries to unmarshal it. The format mismatch will cause failures.\n\n4. **encoder/encoder.go - softEncoder.encode is a stub**: The encode function just copies raw image bytes as \"H.264 NALU\" without any actual H.264 encoding. The comment says \"实际需要调用FFmpeg CGO进行H.264编码\". This means the recording will not be valid H.264.\n\n5. **mp4/mp4.go - WritePacket writes raw NAL units without proper MP4 muxing**: The MP4 writer just writes NAL length prefix + raw data without proper MP4 container format (no moov/mdat boxes, no codec info). The generated files won't be playable.\n\n6. **Go module has duplicate/unused dependency**: `gocv-io/x/go-cv` is listed as indirect but `gocv.io/x/gocv` is also there. These might conflict.\n\n### Moderate Issues:\n\n7. **storage/gc.go line 49 - potentially wrong calculation**: `g.deleteOldest(totalSize - maxBytes*80/100)` - this might not correctly target 80% threshold due to integer math precision.\n\n8. **WebRTC signaling path is broken**: Between the frontend sending malformed SDP strings, the API server not handling WebSocket upgrades, and the webrtc.go having a no-op WriteVideoFrame, WebRTC monitoring will not work at all.\n\n9. **audio.py - fake audio detection**: Audio detection works on video frame data, not actual audio streams. This is acknowledged in comments but fundamentally broken for actual baby monitoring use case.\n\n### Minor Issues:\n\n10. **LiveView.vue has `ws` defined but type is wrong**: `ws` is declared as `let ws = null` but is used as WebSocket, while in main.js there's no App.vue navbar layout visible.\n\nNow let me fix the most critical issues.\n\nActually, let me think about what I can actually fix within the scope of a review. The key principle from the instructions is: \"发现\n\n问题直接用 Edit/Bash 修复目标项目文件\". So I should fix what I can.\n\nThe issues that would require significant rewriting (>30% of files) should be noted as \"需要重跑 DO 阶段\".\n\nLet me determine which issues are quick fixes vs. fundamental problems:\n\nQuick fixes (small edits):\n1. Fix `handleWebRTCSignal` in api/server.go to actually handle WebSocket\n2. Fix `WriteVideoFrame` in webrtc/webrtc.go to actually write frames\n3. Fix the WebSocket message format issue in LiveView.vue or webrtc.go\n\nMajor rewrites needed:\n4. Actual H.264 encoding (requires FFmpeg CGO integration)\n5. Proper MP4 muxing (requires FFmpeg CGO integration)\n\nSo I should fix the quick fixes and note the major issues. Let me start by addressing the WebRTC signaling and video frame writing - these are isolated problems that don't require architectural changes.\n\nFor `handleWebRTCSignal`, I need to implement proper WebSocket upgrade using gorilla/websocket or similar, and for `WriteVideoFrame` I need to actually send the encoded frames through the track. The message format mismatch between the frontend sending SDP as a string and the backend expecting JSON also needs alignment.\n\nLooking at the WebRTC implementation more carefully, `WriteVideoFrame` receives an `interface{}` type but never actually writes anything to the track. The frames just get discarded. And for the API server, it's not upgrading HTTP connections to WebSocket at all - it's just calling `c.Next()` which passes through to the next middleware, but there's nothing there to handle it.\n\nTo fix this properly, I'd need to integrate gorilla/websocket into the Gin handler and properly handle the WebSocket upgrade for signaling messages.\n\nNow looking at the Frontend issue - when it sends an offer via WebSocket, it's stringifying the SDP directly as the payload, but the backend webrtc.go is expecting to parse that payload as JSON. The SDP is just a raw string, not a JSON object, so the unmarshaling will fail when it tries to parse \"v=0\\r\\no=-...\" as JSON.\n\nThere's also a structural mismatch in the Go code - webrtc.go is calling `w.signalCh <- &SignalMessage{...}` to send signals through a channel, but the API server's handleWebRTCSignal function never actually reads from that channel or forwards the WebRTC signals to the client via WebSocket. These pieces aren't connected.\n\nThe fixes needed are: properly implementing WriteVideoFrame to actually write to the track, implementing the WebSocket handler in handleWebRTCSignal to read from signalCh and forward messages to clients, fixing the frontend's JSON-stringified SDP payload to match what the backend expects, and correcting the signaling flow so the backend properly marshals the SessionDescription instead of treating the SDP string as JSON.\n\nActually, stepping back - the whole WebRTC signaling infrastructure is fundamentally broken because the IPC channel between the API server and webrtc server isn't being used at all, the API server doesn't properly upgrade WebSocket connections, and WriteVideoFrame is a no-op. Rather than trying to patch this piecemeal, I should note that this is a systemic issue requiring a proper redesign of the signaling flow.\n\nFor the review though, I'll tackle the straightforward fixes: WriteVideoFrame should actually write to the track, handleWebRTCSignal should properly upgrade connections and relay messages, and the frontend/backend message format should be consistent. I also notice go.mod has a duplicate gocv dependency that should be cleaned up. Let me start with these targeted improvements.","signature":"7372fa6f55b46b72b57a1b4e8077bb5d9a5235df619401c1c12bc91102733e9e"}],"model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":50821,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":19028},"service_tier":"standard","context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c7030919-046f-4d40-9d16-8b74cebd40f3","uuid":"0c394cbc-4809-46de-a60f-1418510ae478"}
